# Document: Thai and Burmese Workers (SOC Worker Analysis)

This document explains the SOC worker-attendance data so the chatbot can read the
eleven data tables correctly. All figures come from the daily attendance records of
the three departments; this document defines the terms, and the eleven tables hold
the numbers.

## Thai vs Burmese (nationality)

Every worker is supplied by a staffing **vendor** (also called the "Sub-con"). Each
vendor is classified as **Thai** or **Burmese**:

- **Thai vendors:** PPO, WAS, RG, YSL, BigBoom.
- **Every other vendor counts as Burmese** by default. (If a new vendor is Thai, it
  is added to the Thai list; until then it is treated as Burmese.)

Every number in the tables is split into a **Burmese** row and a **Thai** row —
there is **no combined "both nationalities" row**. If a department has only Burmese
workers, only Burmese rows appear.

## Departments and teams

- **Departments (SOC):** **SOCN, SOCE, SOCW**. Each is reported separately.
- **Teams (stations), 8 in total:** **IB, CBS, mCBS, MS, OBI, OBC, OBS, OBD**.
- **`All`** in the Team column = the whole department (all teams combined) for that
  nationality. (Exception: the Rotation table has **no `All` row** — see below.)
- **Three time grains — `Month`, `Week`, `Day`** — each grain is a **SEPARATE FILE**
  per aspect (see "How to read the eleven data tables" below), not a column you
  filter within one shared table.
  - `Month` file: `Period` is a short month label (e.g. `Jun`).
  - `Week` file: `Period` is an ISO week label (e.g. `W23`). A week can straddle
    two months; it is attributed to whichever month contains most of that week's
    activity in the source data.
  - `Day` file: `Period` is a calendar date `YYYY-MM-DD` (e.g. `2026-06-05`).
  - The `Year` column carries the year (month/week labels alone don't).
  - **Consecutive has no `Day` file** (there is no daily consecutive metric — only
    `Consecutive Month` and `Consecutive Week` exist).
  - **`Day`-file rows only exist where someone was present**: if a (Team,
    Nationality, Day) row is absent from the Day file, the count for that day is
    **zero**.
  - **Normalize month references to the short label**: a full month name
    (`June`), a Thai month word (`มิถุนายน`), or any other variant all mean the
    same `Period` as `Jun`. Match on the normalized month, not the literal string.

## Metric definitions (one line each)

- **New / Old face** — classifies only workers who stayed at **one** station that
  month. **Old** (experienced) = one station **and ≥10 working days**; **New**
  (inexperienced) = one station **and <10 days**. Workers who **rotated** between
  stations that month are **excluded** here — they appear in Rotation.
- **Show Up** — how many days each worker showed up in that period, grouped into
  buckets. **Monthly buckets are `1_5, 6_10, 11_15, 16_20, 21_30`** days (column
  names use underscores, not hyphens — a hyphenated range like `1-5` reads as a
  date shorthand to some tools, so the columns are named to avoid that).
  **Weekly buckets are a DIFFERENT, smaller set: `1_2, 3_4, 5_7`** days (a week
  can't hold a 21-30-day count). Each worker falls in exactly one bucket for that
  period; the bucket counts sum to that scope's total workers for the period.
- **3-day Consecutive** — whether a worker worked at least **3 days in a row** at
  least once in the month. Workers are first split by attendance (**<10** vs **>10**
  days), then by streak history (**used to** have a ≥3-day run vs **never** did). The
  "Active" count is the month's total workers (the <10 + >10 split).
- **Rotation** — for a given team: **Rotation** = the worker worked more than once
  that month AND also worked at other teams (moved around); **Non Rotation** = stayed
  put. **"1 day"** (OneDay) = a non-rotated worker who came only a single day that
  month. Because a worker can be counted at several teams, Rotation has **no `All`
  department-total row** (it would double-count movers).

A month-over-month change of **≥5 percentage points** is considered **notable**
(up = improving, down = declining).

## How to read the eleven data tables

Each **(aspect × grain)** combination is its own separate spreadsheet file, one flat
`data` table — **11 files total**, since a metric that doesn't apply at a given grain
(e.g. Show Up's day-count buckets don't exist for a single day) used to leave BLANK
cells in a shared table, which broke automated ingestion. Splitting by grain means
every file has ONLY the columns that are actually populated — no file ever has a
blank cell. **Picking the right FILE is now part of answering the question — there
is no single "Show Up" table to filter by a `Grain` column anymore.**

The 11 files (all share the first six columns: **Department, Nationality, Team,
Year, Grain, Period** — `Grain` is constant within each file, included for clarity):

| Aspect | Month file | Week file | Day file |
|---|---|---|---|
| New-Old Face | `New-Old Face Month` | `New-Old Face Week` | `New-Old Face Day` |
| Show Up | `Show Up Month` | `Show Up Week` | `Show Up Day` |
| Consecutive | `Consecutive Month` | `Consecutive Week` | *(none — no daily metric)* |
| Rotation | `Rotation Month` | `Rotation Week` | `Rotation Day` |

- **New-Old Face** (Month/Week/Day — identical columns in all three)
  `... | Old | New | Old% | New%`
  - `Month`/`Week` files: Old/New = classified workers for that period; Old%/New% = their shares.
  - `Day` file: Old/New = workers **present that day**, counted by their MONTH
    verdict (rotated workers excluded, so Old + New ≤ that day's head count).
- **Show Up Month** — `... | 1_5 | 6_10 | 11_15 | 16_20 | 21_30 | Total | 1_5% | 6_10% | 11_15% | 16_20% | 21_30%`
  (the five day-count buckets; `Total` = workers that month; each `%` = that bucket's share of Total)
- **Show Up Week** — `... | 1_2 | 3_4 | 5_7 | Total | 1_2% | 3_4% | 5_7%`
  (a DIFFERENT, smaller bucket set than Month — do not confuse the two files' columns)
- **Show Up Day** — `... | Total` only. `Total` = the **distinct head count** present
  that day (no buckets or percentages exist at daily grain — that's why it's a
  separate file with just this one column).
  - **Never open the Day file and sum its `Total` values to answer a monthly
    question.** Each Day row's `Total` counts everyone present that specific day;
    the same worker appears in a fresh row every day they show up, so summing
    several days multiplies people by days present, not a real headcount. If the
    user asks for a monthly figure, open `Show Up Month` and read the single
    matching row's `Total` directly — never derive it from `Show Up Day`.
- **Consecutive Month** — `... | ShowUp<10 | ShowUp>10 | Active | UsedTo3day<10 | UsedTo3day>10 | Never3day<10 | Never3day>10 | UsedTo3day% | Never3day%`
  (Active = ShowUp<10 + ShowUp>10; UsedTo3day% and Never3day% are shares of Active.)
- **Consecutive Week** — `... | GreaterEq3Consecutive | Less3NonConsecutive | Active | GreaterEq3% | Less3%`
  (a DIFFERENT, simpler shape than Month: just two streak categories for that week,
  not the Month file's ShowUp<10/>10 split. `Active` = GreaterEq3Consecutive + Less3NonConsecutive.)
- **Rotation Month** / **Rotation Week** (identical columns) — `... | NonRotation | Rotation | Total | OneDay | OneDay%OfNonRot | NonRotation% | Rotation%`
  (**No `All` row in either** — Rotation is inherently about movement between teams,
  so a department-wide aggregate would double-count a worker who rotated across
  several teams. Total = NonRotation + Rotation; OneDay%OfNonRot = OneDay ÷ NonRotation.)
- **Rotation Day** — `... | NonRotation | Rotation | Total | NonRotation% | Rotation%`
  (`OneDay` doesn't exist at daily grain, so this file has fewer columns than
  Month/Week — NonRotation/Rotation = workers **present that day** by their MONTH
  Reading-B status at that team. No `All` row here either.)

To answer a question: **first pick the correct (aspect, grain) file** for what's
being asked, then find the ONE row matching the asked Department + Nationality +
Team + Period + Year, quote its exact figure, and name that file and scope. If more
than one row seems to match within a file, that means Period differs somewhere —
re-check before using either one, and never combine rows into a bigger number, and
never combine numbers pulled from two different files.
